<br>
For example using root to crowd control as Chipp mentioned is one way to distinguish us. But it takes time to learn that versatility and play our class well. Things like using a heal on   the puller to get some extra aggro, or root the mobs that beat on a chanter take time to master and require you to pay attention. <br>
<br>
Sadly too often people only remember the worse example of a class, e.g. a paladin that never uses his spells or a necro that only nukes and sics pet. That's how too many people classify a class.<br>
<br>
If you use your skills well you can do things that sound unbelievable to others. Couple weeks ago I wanted to try the paladin powers to break and hold chef room in sebilis with a none perfect group. I played my 60 pal, 56 chanter and 52 druid for healing. <br>
<br>
Using waves of prexus to draw aggro gave the chanter chance to mez the typical 4 pull on chef break. A quick hotkey to /assist /root a mez resist mob gave the chanter room to cast. Any loose mobs I taunted with a quick stun. The main mobs still beating me I rooted and stepped back. Using our spells made the difference. <br>
<br>
If you would replace the paladin with a warrior they would have failed miserable. <br>
